European foulbrood of honey bees, Malta
---------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 27 Aug 2015 from Dr Anthony Gruppetta , Officer in scale 3, Veterinary Regulation and Fisheries Conservation and Control, Veterinary Affairs and Fisheries Division Ministry of Rural Affairs and Environment, Marsa, Malta

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 4 Jun 2015
Date of confirmation of the event: 12 Jun 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2005
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: _Melissococcus plutonius_
Nature of diagnosis: suspicion, clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (2)
Outbreak 1: Mellieha, Qammieh, Ghadira, Malta [Northern Region]
Date of start of the outbreak: 4 Jun 2015
Outbreak status: resolved 16 Jun 2015
Epidemiological unit: apiary
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Bees (hives) / 10 / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0
Affected population: The owner is a small holder of only these 10 susceptible hives which he holds at only one site.

Outbreak 2: AG14, Ta"Wilga, Mgarr, Malta [Northern Region]
Date of start of the outbreak: 26 Aug 2015
Outbreak status: resolved 27 Aug 2015
Epidemiological unit: apiary
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Bees (hives) / 5 / 1 / 0 / 1 / 0
Affected population: The owner keeps hives on various sites but to date only this site is affected.

Summary of outbreaks: Total outbreaks: 2
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Bees (hives) / 15 / 2 / 0 / 2 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Bees (hives) / 13.33 / 0 / 0 / 13.33
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: fomites (humans, vehicles, feed, etc.)

Control measures
Measures applied: screening, disinfection/disinfestations; modified stamping out; no vaccination; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Now Sweden and Malta join the Czech Republic (see report below) as countries where European foulbrood has been reported. The increase in reported cases of this and other bee diseases may be due to the improved surveillance and detection efforts implemented by many Member country veterinary services, and which the OIE has been encouraging and helping to develop.

For more information, the subscriber may want to refer to:

OIE Editorial: "Protecting bees to safeguard our future" -- Dr Bernard Vallat, Director General of the OIE. http://www.oie.int/en/for-the-media/editorials/detail/article/protecting-bees-to-safeguard-our-future/.

OIE Bulletin no 2, 2014: "Protecting bees, preserving our future," available at http://tinyurl.com/lv2ly6o.

"General introductory text providing background information for the chapters of the Terrestrial Animal Health Code on disease of bees": http://www.oie.int/en/our-scientific-expertise/specific-information-and-recommendations/bee-diseases/.
- Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing Sweden is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3606909,19544;
and Malta, at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3606909,77.]
